subsection.p:
Revisiting the mixing problem that we posed at the beginning of this section, we have the following initial value problem,
\frac{dx}{dt} & = - \frac{5}{3} x, \frac{dy}{dt} & = \frac{5}{3} x - \frac{5}{3} y. x(0) & = 100, y(0) & = 0.
Solving dx/dt = - (5/3) x is easy. We can quickly determine that x(t) = c_1 e^{-5t/3}. Applying the initial condition x(0) = 100, we can determine that c_1 = 100 and x(t) = 100 e^{-5t/3}. Our second equation now becomes \frac{dy}{dt} = \frac{5}{3} x - \frac{5}{3} y = \frac{500}{3} e^{-5t/3} - \frac{5}{3} y. This last equation is a first-order linear equation \frac{dy}{dt} + \frac{5}{3} y = \frac{500}{3} e^{-5t/3}. Multiplying both sides of this last equation by the integrating factor \mu(t) = e^{5t/3} yields \frac{d}{dt} (e^{5t/3}y) = e^{5t/3}\frac{dy}{dt} + e^{5t/3}\frac{5}{3} y = \frac{500}{3}. Integrating both sides of this last equation gives us e^{5t/3}y = \frac{500}{3} t + c_2. Using our initial condition y(0) = 0, we can determine that c_2 = 0. Thus, y = \frac{500}{3} t e^{-5t/3}
